metadata.name: TENDER Pass #638
metadata.description:
Tender is a curatorial platform and community that helps bring incredible works of generative art to discerning collectors.

Holding a TENDER Pass enables enriched benefits and experiences within the Tender ecosystem. Passholders expand their access to unique collaborations with extraordinary artists, indispensable collector tools, curatorial experiences, artwork insights, fine art prints, a thriving community, and more.

Tender is committed to stewarding the growth of generative art and amplifying the voices of artists and collectors across the entire lifecycle: from creation to collection to curation, and back again. Every Pass minted and resold directly enables Tender to continue creating the platform and experiences that serve this mission.

——

TENDER Pass features unique artwork by punevyr. While all Passes are special, a small number of randomly generated, rarified tokens will come with boosted benefits. If you have a piece with a dark background of any kind, you likely possess one of the following:

Bonus Pass
TENDER Passes with the special Bonus trait get 1 guaranteed reserve spot on all TENDER x Collab projects

Grail Pass
TENDER Passes with the special Grail trait get 2 free mints on all TENDER x Collab projects


New Passholders may access our Discord server that’s linked from our website.
For TENDER Pass benefits and up-to-date details, please visit tender.art/pass


Artwork created with p5.js

---

TENDER x punevyr
July 2022

metadata.name: Intangible #73
metadata.description:
Let me take you places. Those are not in your town, not even on your planet. They’re placed somewhere between reality and subconsciousness.
Enormous, peculiar structures emerge upon you, refusing to be ignored. They are your unfulfilled cravings or ever-lurking demons. They were always there, under your skin, intangible, now they’ve materialized.
You may not like them, they may seem too vast, too scary to tame. But ultimately, you have to face them, unless you enjoy living in their shadow. 

___
Inspirations

I’ve never truly realized that, but ever since I remember, the sight of gigantic objects or creatures evoked strong emotions within me.
It probably started with playing Shadow of Colossus (a video game) as a kid and seeing The Cathedral (short movie by Tomasz Bagiński). Years later, reading Solaris (by Stanisław Lem) aroused the same feeling (among others) of being mesmerized by the vastness. More recently, movies like Denis Villeneuve’s Arrival (which also nudged my attraction to mystery) and Dune - have charmed me.

Earlier this year I have stumbled across Dawid Planeta (artist and yoga teacher) and began contemplating his visions of mini people in the jungle inhabited by giant animals. These works in particular, plus Hollow - generative series by Jacek Markusiewicz - were probably my final inspirations to make Intangible look the way it does.

Settling semi-random generative structures in some kind of reality, gave them a meaning - they may symbolize things much bigger than you - the ones you try to escape from or those you’ve been longing to experience for years. I have mine, don’t you?

___
Controls in live mode


Keyboard
[ space ] - toggle light animation
[ S ] - save image with current size (default is 120% of browser window’s height; you may change browser’s scale or check URL size param)
[ F ] - fullscreen 
[ up / down ] - light intensity
[ left / right ] - base light position
[ 1..5 ] - aspect ratio: 10:16 („zero” ratio), 1:1.4142 (vertical A4), 1:1, 1.4142 (horizontal A4), 16:10
[ B ] - toggle border
[ Z ] - toggle canvas „raw” mode - no shadow / margin (auto applied in fullscreen mode)
[ N ] - toggle „that thing you may not want on print”


URL params
You may add any number of parameters to the URL to start it with particular settings. 
[ animate ] (1/0) - toggle light animation
[ size] (number) - number of px for longer edge, i.e. 4000
[ ratio ] (number or ratio with format: 10/16, 10:16, 10_16) - aspect ratio
[ light ] (number 40..120, some palettes have slightly different limits for good results) - light intensity
[ lightShift] (number -100..100) - base light position
[ border ] (1/0) - toggle border
[ hddcy ] (0/1)

Example: [ &size=4000&border=1&light=100&animate=1 ] 


Mobile
[hold 2 fingers for 2s] - save
[double tap] - fullscreen


___
Note:
I encourage you to do some light adjustments before you save an image for print. I’m pretty sure you can do better than fxrand().


___
Special thanks to my brother Krzycho, for lots of advices / heathy criticism and to Olga, for never-ending excitement and „dorady”.

___
Developed in Javascript, using p5.js (2D Canvas) and chroma.js.

metadata.name: GuilCity #333
metadata.description:
GuilCity is the beginning of an exciting journey bringing Guillaume Cornet’s densely-packed cities into the generative realm with the help of Matthew’s (@frostbitten’s) magic touch.

Matthew—with his background in coding and animation—enables a new opportunity to experience these cities like never before. Numerous elements from vehicles to characters and even architecture have been given life. Interact with the city (computer mouse only): poke and peek around (even behind) in this active search & find journey! 

Each generative city fills the composition with the type of whimsical, expressive elements and characters you’ve come to know Guil for. What kinds of wacky features have you discovered yet?

—

The tech behind this project utilizes the highly compressed WEBP image format in order to provide so many full-color options. This format is great, but unfortunately Safari on desktop/laptop must be upgraded to at least version 14 and macOS to at least version 11 Big Sur to use it.

The animation system for this project was created from scratch with additional help from the PIXI.js library for individual mesh animations.

—

To find out more about your GuilCity, copy your unique operation hash and place it at the end of the following url:
• https://my.guil.city?fxhash=
(for example: https://my.guil.city?fxhash=ooezL8cffNJGSc4TfNQp3u3WnDpkg8J3zFRczLuumceoYU5QYPs)

—


The entire process has been a learning experience for both of us, adapting and exploring the many possibilities to interact with each others’ skills and ideas.

We really enjoyed building this project together and are excited as we invite you to take a dive into your very own urban playground!

Merci à tous! Cheers!
  - Guillaume Cornet, Matthew Seremet

metadata.name: Ersbla #938
metadata.description:
Ersbla is part of the fxhash live minting experience at Proof of People, London 2022. 

It is the third entry in a series of abstract generative experiments inspired by the graphic and textile work of Anni and Josef Albers. As a follow-up to the 'Sabler' and 'Lebras' collections, 'Ersbla' produces textile effects using a combination of thousands of tiny dots arranged on variable grids, resulting in a wide variety of unique Bauhaus-inspired compositions in a variety of palettes.

Press 'S' to save a high-resolution 2400 x 3396 px image in PNG format.

Depending on the density of your output, please allow up to a few seconds for your edition to generate.

metadata.name: DisOrder #401
metadata.description:
Manual Dutch Auction (DA): 84 · 56 · 38 · 26 · 18  every 8 minutes.
Auction will stop changing price when non-reserves are fully minted.

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////

All that is, starts with Order.

Order attempts to evade entropy by following its own intrinsic patterns. Then, inevitably, there is change: an anomaly, a nudge that turns into a catalyst for widespread change.The momentum cannot be stopped.

Brief cycles build upon themselves, iterating and breaking into something new with each turn. Now, looking back, the accumulation of small divergences look like a leap, with trails of evolutionary decline casting tall shadows on the patterns that bore them.

The beauty of what this entropy creates, rises beyond chaos. It represents the past, and signals the future, and suddenly looks like a wild take on Order itself – the true DisOrder of life.

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////

FEATURES :
21 Features implemented including colors, styles, technical parameters...

INTERACTIVITY :
Press ‘h’ in live mode for a list of options.
Press 's' to save an image of the output at the current resolution
Press ‘1’-’9’ to increase resolution
...

metadata.name: BULLET #176
Circles In A Square World #135
metadata.description:
Circles In A Square World, is a play on the saying "being square", usually referring to someone who is more conventional and boring. In the society I grew up in, being square is what people are being pushed towards. A traditional 9 - 5 in a well paying office job the goal. But I believe that in a world where the majority is square, living the circle life is way more fulfilling.

For each square in Circles In A Square World there is a small chance a circle will be drawn instead. The series re-uses the palettes that were discovered in Ode to Color as well. 

To watch the drawing process press 'd'.

To get a higher resolution for printing add ?size=4096 at the end of the URL in the live view (you can use any size you want).

metadata.name: Isomeric doppelgangers #72
metadata.description:
'Isomeric doppelgangers' 

Spatial isomerism, is a form of isomerism in which molecules have the same molecular formula and sequence of bonded atoms (constitution), but differ in the three-dimensional orientations of their atoms in space.

This artworks flips several boxes on the X or Y axis, resulting in two gemelar images, each with the same palette but a different color mix. The perception of diverse scenes is based only on these modifications.

The collection is limited to 100 works of art.

-----

Press 's' to save the current canvas view.

-----

Features:

Palette: coral, gray, retro, vrolik3, origami, sooph, jfa, bell
Zoom: low, medium, high, random
Orientation: portrait, vertical
Fill: true, false


-----

Artwork by @cristianrohr.

Made with P5js and <3.

metadata.name: Landscapes in my mind #25
metadata.description:
In this work I tried to convey the idea of a landscape (many landscapes) with hills, trees, grass, bushes, skies and clouds. As is normal on fxhash I have accomplished all this by writing the code that generates the elements in a scene.
While writing the code to obtain these landscapes I did not try to reproduce landscapes seen in reality or in photography, rather I followed from time to time ideas of landscapes that came to my mind as a sort of lucid dream. I hope I managed to convey this idea of a landscape that is halfway between reality and fantasy.

Lands and Clouds are rendered using a mix of simplex noise and FBM (Fractional Brownian Motion), trees are generated with recursive functions an placed using Poisson Disk Sampling distribution. The distribution density could be homogeneous (land heightmap drive the density) or biased to have more density towards the top, bottom, left or right of the land.


Developed with p5.js using WEBGL renderer.
Rendering is faster with chrome browser.

[1] to render at 1600x1600
[2] to render at 2400x2400
[3] to render at 3200x3200
[s] to save a png at last rendered resolution.


Features:
"LandPalette": 20 colormaps
"TreePalette": 20 colormaps
"Light":  Morning, Evening, Night
"SkyColor": Blue, Azure, Turquoise, Gray, VioletRed
"Haze": True, False
"Rainbow":  True, False
"Grayscale": True, False
"TreeDensity": Homogeneous, Top, Bottom, Left, Right


Created by Andrea Belloni, fxhash: anbello, twitter: @Waterflowing0. Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, see LICENSE.txt for more information.

metadata.name: 7VV1N5 #335
metadata.description:
GO BIG OR GO HOME.

After a week of minimalism code, our hero, the handsome artist Daniel, decided he needed something involving maximalism to reset the balance. Finding pairs to put together is satisfying.

Images will take 6-9 seconds to display and refresh between window resizing.

Use the z key or single click/tap to switch to "zoom" mode, which zooms in and fills the viewport; use z & tap/click to cycle through views. Use x and double-click/tap to go back to square mode.

Note: It doesn't work on Internet Explorer, because Microsoft. iOS is faster than Android.

-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-=-

z, click, tap - Switch to & cycle "zoom" mode
x, double-click, double-tap - Switch back out of "zoom" mode.
h - Toggle high-res (slow)
s - Download and save image (takes a few seconds, longer for high-res)

metadata.name: Consequence Broadcast [Speed Run] #79
metadata.description:
a.k.a. Reaction Diffusion. The canvas is a grid of cells, each containing some amount of A and some amount of B. Every step, A and B react with each other and diffuse into neighbouring cells. The amounts of diffusion and reaction have different settings, which can vary across the canvas or over time. Then, cool things happen with colours. 

This is an experimental project, created as part of a Speed Run over ~37 hours in one weekend (I did also sleep and eat in that time. I even went for a walk. Go me). 
- It requires WEBGL2 and is GPU intensive. 
- There may be slight discrepancies in the patterns on different devices, due to rounding. 

Big thanks to everyone who followed along/offered advice and especially to Piter Pasma who helped me out with the noise dithering code that took everything to the next dimension.

Press P to pause.
Press 1-5 to alter speed.

metadata.name: brushstroke #19
metadata.description:
Brushstroke is an algorithm to form a minimal, modern, artistic paint on a canvas. It mimics a painter's hand gesture to apply different types of strokes. Those strokes may vary from thin straight lines to fat curvy arcs. The direction of the strokes may change for each stroke or not. There may be an excessive amount of them as there may be just several. Strokes may intersect and form a group. It generates color palettes as an artist does. There are more than twenty parameters that give variety to pieces. 

Brushstroke is built on the p5.js library. As a way of saying thanks, you will contribute to the Processing Foundation by collecting this work.
